WHEREAS, after retiring from the bench, John Brown and his wife, Anne, spent a year
in the Republic of Georgia after he was selected for the competitive American Bar Association
CEELI Program, through which he helped train judges on the court system of a new democracy
governed by the rule of law; and
WHEREAS, during his retirement, he continued to serve as Senior Judge and work as a
pharmacist, and he even tried his hand at selling cars with Lexus of Nashville; and
WHEREAS, he further served his community as a volunteer with Operation Stand Down,
a program that helps veterans with legal issues, housing, and jobs; he began his work with the
program when it was in its infancy, and it has since grown to have locations across Middle
Tennessee; and
WHEREAS, John Brown had been a member of Calvary United Methodist Church since
the early 1960s; a devoted man of God, he hosted a weekly men's prayer group consisting of
some of his closest, dearest friends; and
WHEREAS, known for his deep love of Willie Nelson and Family, Judge Brown attended
hundreds of their shows, often joining the band back stage, and eventually worked his way into
Willie's show, joining the band to sing "harmony" with Willie at the end of the band's one
instrumental song and performing countless times to his own adoring fans; he also fulfilled his
lifelong ambition of singing on the stage of the Grand Ole Opry, in addition to many other
venues; and
WHEREAS, his passions also included traveling throughout the country and the world
with his wife, coaching youth football and baseball, and spending time with his family; and
WHEREAS, John Brown is survived by his loving wife of forty years, Anne Drury Brown;
daughter, Joan Brown (Matt) Smith; sons, John P. "Jack" (Cindy) Brown III, Kevin Drury, and
Matt Drury; grandchildren, Leah Hazel Bayston, Thaddeus Scott (Rachel) Bayston, Audrey Ruth
- 2 - 013553

Bayston, Matthew Masin Drury, Jackson Porter Brown, and Isaac Drake Brown; and brothers,
Robert (Susan) Brown and Phillip Brown; and
WHEREAS, in addition to his parents, he was preceded in death by his brother, Tom
Brown; and
WHEREAS, Judge Brown leaves behind an indelible legacy of integrity and probity in
public life, compassion and loyalty in private life, and diligence and dedication in all his chosen
endeavors; and
WHEREAS, it is fitting that the members of this General Assembly should pause to
remember the bountiful life of this exceptional jurist, public servant, and human being; now,
therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that we honor the memory of Judge John P. Brown, reflecting fondly upon his
impeccable character and his stalwart commitment to living the examined life with courage and
conviction.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that we express our sympathy and offer our condolences
to the family of Judge Brown.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
